explanation:
For checking MISRA rule on unreachable code we must know which branches/paths in OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish can actually occur at runtime. The required symbols and why:

1) OS_object_token_t - definition (struct) showing fields lock_mode and obj_id. Needed to determine what values lock_mode can hold and whether obj_id is available for the EXCLUSIVE branch (record->active_id = token->obj_id).

2) OS_common_record_t - definition (struct) showing fields refcount and active_id. Needed to check whether the refcount and active_id accesses are valid and whether the refcount > 0 branch can be reached.

3) OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE - constant/enum value. Required to evaluate the initial early-return condition and determine if that branch can occur.

4) OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE - constant/enum value. Required to determine reachability of both the OS_Lock_Global() call (the OR test) and the later else-if that restores token->obj_id; must know this value relative to others.

5) OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT - constant/enum value. Required because it appears in the OR test that triggers OS_Lock_Global(); important for reachability reasoning of the locking branch.

6) OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL - constant/enum value (or equivalent mode used by the code/locking system). The comment mentions a GLOBAL lock path; need this symbol to understand the case where the global mutex is already held and hence which branches are reachable.

7) OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken - implementation/contract. Needed to know whether it can modify token->lock_mode, return NULL, or otherwise change conditions that affect later branches (e.g., guarantees that record is non-NULL and whether it affects lock state).

8) OS_Lock_Global - implementation/contract. Crucial to know if calling it can change token->lock_mode (for example, set it to GLOBAL) or otherwise alter control-flow/side-effects that make subsequent branches (particularly the later else-if testing for EXCLUSIVE) unreachable.

9) OS_Unlock_Global - implementation/contract. Needed to verify if it expects certain lock_mode states and whether it changes token->lock_mode (e.g., to NONE) before the final assignment; such behavior affects whether code after it could be considered unreachable.

10) OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit - caller/initializer that sets up token->lock_mode. Required to know the set of lock_mode values that can be assigned to the token before OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish is called (i.e., whether EXCLUSIVE/REFCOUNT/GLOBAL/ NONE are actually possible in practice).

Together these symbols let an analyst determine whether any of the conditionals/branches in OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish are impossible given how tokens and locks are initialized and modified, and thus whether any code in the function is statically unreachable.
